autophagy entails the sorting and concentration of small protein aggregates to speciﬁc sites in the cytosol (206–209) with the participation of chaperones such as Hsp42 (small Hsp) (209). These deposition sites include the aggresome, to which components mediating autophagic vacuole formation are recruited (206, 210, 211). Additional pathways of autophagy in-

clude chaperone-mediated autophagy (CMA) and chaperone-assisted selective autophagy (CASA) (198, 200, 212). In CMA, Hsc70 and certain cochaperones bind to a KFERQ sequence motif present in approximately 30% of all cytoplasmic proteins. This complex binds the lysosomal membrane protein LAMP2, followed by translocation of the substrate

